Best to print with .1 res you can do more but you will need to sand the spindle and pin. Makes the holder easy to remove if needed and raises it up a bit more for a better feed angle. It sits on the original spool mount point and clamps the sides very well. It can be printed on the monoprice mini select too :) I added the spool center made to fit Hatchbox spools. This centers the larger spool on the spindle so the edges won't drag on the front of the hanger. It is slightly undersized intentionally. I put a strip double sided tape around the holder to stick it to the spool. This way it is semi-permanent but can be removed when the spool is empty. I did not have any other examples of large spools to make other versions but adjusting it for your spools should be easy enough. For really small spools, or almost used up spools I drag the holder closer to the top of the printer to have a straighter feed for the filament. I keep it there with a few small magnets under the spool holder. Simple and works well.

description.text:
Adam Jochna posted a printed micro switch. I thought is was quite clever to utilize an inexpensive 1/4 inch tactile switch. Here's his posting: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:756126

I designed a similar part, but it includes several enhancements. First, I didn't like having exposed terminals. So, I made side covers that have slots for wires to escape out the bottom.

Second, the 2-piece body/lever was difficult to make work correctly. Too much trimming had to be done to get a nice, smooth action, without making it too wobbly. So, I integrated a hinged lever to the body. The movement is clean and the lever has no side play.

After the parts are made, clean up any flash that may be on the bottom layer of the prints. Pay particular attention to the hinge area. If that isn't clear of flash, the lever won't flex very well.

Cut one terminal of each pole of the switch (see picture). The terminals are pass-through, so you only need one side for it to work. Solder wires to the remaining terminals. You can fit up to #20 wire inside the slot that's formed with the covers (#24 wires are shown in the example). Then, wiggle the switch into position under the lever.

Sandwich the switch between the left and right side covers and mount it with small screws.

I made the lever extra long so you can easily trim it to length with a razor blade or wire cutter.

Hello all,
These are parts for thing:231205 by peddiparth.
Motor mounts have 25mm spacing. see instructions for more info!

parts list.
3x 1/2" wooden dowels. my front 2 are cut to about 14 inches and the aft is about 12 1/2. you can change the lengths if needed... 10x #6 32x1in machine screws (got mine at home depot) they come with nuts but I bought locknuts and washers which is optional. I would suggest using Loctite at the very least. super glue 2 bearings 5x13x4 (I,O,W) 1CF tube or rod, aluminum could work, 5mmx50mm ball links and pushrod for tail. electronics I used are:
exceed rc rocket series 3010-1100Kv motors (lots of power)
20A escs (got mine from quadrysteria but had to reflash with a different version of simonk)
KK2.1 flight controller
3S 4000mah 30C lipo
digital metal geared servo for tail, 9-11g is fine. The battery tray is glued together, spacers are not glued on.
The tail is a little more complicated.
insert 1st bearing into motor mount, put plastic spacer onto CF rod and slide it on until there is 4mm of CF rod sticking out, insert the 4mm into the bearing in the motor mount. NOTE: if the spacer is not a VERY tight fit, add a very small drop of glue to hold it on the rod.
slide the other bearing onto the other end of the tube and press into motor mount, it should be flush. slide the tailcap onto the CF rod and press against the motor mount, glue the tailcap onto the motor mount, this holds the bearings in! the spacer in turn holds everything in place..... drill a 35mm deep hole into your dowel that you are using for the tail (straight and centered as possible). I used an 11/64th drillbit I think, it is just under 5mm but makes the CF tube a friction fit so you don't need to glue it in. Press the CF tube into hole (make sure your tail servo mount/gear is on first) and leave about 1mm of clearance between the two. add the servo and pushrod and go fly! you can tap that yaw mount into the boom with a hammer if needed!

This is the second version of the Carabiner I made a little while ago. I made the other one with Nylon in mind as the print material. Nylon is really strong but it's a pain in the butt to print so I wanted to make one that could hold my weight in ABS or PLA. I don't have a lot of experience with PLA but I think it's at least as strong as ABS. I printed this at 50% size in green ABS. The carabiner in the picture is 5.5" and 7/8" thick. It's a good chunk of plastic but it needs to be pretty big to be strong in ABS. I hung a swing from it in my basement and it easily held my weight (uh, lets say less than 200lbs). Be careful if you try it. Don't use it for climbing or safety critical applications.

I made this with Tinkercad and openscad. Tinkercad for the body and scad for the screw threads. The body is all original, the screw threads I modified from a script by NielsJL in the Tinkercad Community. BTW his script is modified from an example in the SCAD program itself. It is the only thread design, and I mean the ONLY one that will produce a configurable nut and bolt that will print reliably in Nylon. I've tried pretty much everything out there. The hinge on my carabiner opens sideways because support material becomes an issue if it is printed to open in the "normal" way. Print the carabiner horizontally and the nut vertically.. description.text:
Update: Added mod that tilts the fan 10 deg towards the front of the cab and has more clearance towards the motherboard. Files marked.

Disclaimer: This mod is made for the Gigabyte GTX 1070 Windforce 2X OC. Check images for similarity with your graphics card. Original SLDPRT's can made be available on demand. I do not take any responsibility for you or your graphics card condition before, during or after installation.

This mod is made with the purpose of decreasing the noise level of the GTX 1070. Typical temp on the card on my system playing PUBG is 65 deg C, with a fan speed of +-1000 RPM

It is highly recommended to use a "advanced" fan controller (e.g. Corsair Commander Pro), to enable control of the fan speed based on the GPU temperature.

You need:
2 M3x20 bolts
2 M3 nuts
4 3,2 mm washers
1 Noctua NF-A14 PWM (or similar)

Installation description:
1.Remove the 7 bolts holding the cooler to the card.

  1. Carefully remove the cooler, and remove the connector for the fans.
  2. Remove the 2 bolts in each end of the cooler, to remove the fan shroud (4 bolts total).
  3. It is now recommended to remove and apply new thermal paste, and inspect the condition of the thermal pads. Replace if necessary.
  4. Slide the two main parts of the new fan mod in on the cooling block. The offset part shall face outwards (power connector side).
  5. Bolt the two parts together with the M3 bolts, nuts and washers.
  6. Glue on the end stops on each side of the new fan mod, preventing the mod to slide of.
  7. Install the fan, using the complimentary Noctua fan mounts.
  8. Install the new cooler on the card, opposite order of step no 2 and 1.
  9. Go have fun!

description.text:
Designed to remove small pills from blister packs more easily. Especially for those with weak hands/fingers. Maximum pill size (round ones) is about 6mm. The larger one is for 7-10mm pills.

NOTE: with powdery tablets it is advisable to break the seal before pushing out the tablet to avoid damaging the tablet. the larger version has very small spikes around the edge to assist in breaking the seal on larger blister packs.

Best printed with Flexi PLA and Standard PLA - After first few layers in flexi, pause and put in standard PLA. See printing info below.

Or print the whole thing with Flexi PLA or even TPU as long as you use high infill - 60% or more.

The models above were printed in White Flexi PLA to 0.7mm, the printer was then paused, standard PLA filament was put in, and the print resumed to completion. (Assumes 0.3 first layer and 0.2mm layer height).

EDIT 14/12/2017: pill_popper_07 and pill_popper_07_LARGE files replace old ones with clearer pins on foil side plus previous 06 modes had a few errors.

This can be printed in PLA/ABS or PETG however, if flexable filament is not used for the first 2/3 layers it will need heating post printing to "fold" the thin middle section so it is permanently bent to sit over a blister pack (Hot water or a hot air gun - fold and cool).

Best printed in two filaments (Pausing will do) Print base layers in Flexi PLA and then standard PLA. High infill and 3 layers are recommended to make sure the button does not break off.

title: Replicator 2X Extruder Upgrade for Flexible Filament

description.text:
Made some minor changes to the awesome upgrade designed by rmcniff: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:222667

Original remix by rmcniff improved printing with NinjaFlex and other flexible filaments, but I often would still have to continually clean the nozzle after every print and it would often jam during the print, forcing me to restart.

Fixed a few crucial dimensions to provide better extrusion and have had great results so far.

  1. Added an additional upper filament guide tube above the gear. Although the lower guide hole helped, I still had problems with the filament bunching up above the gear. This provides an even more directed path for the filament.
  2. Increased height of the base below the spring to increase the compression of the spring. I had an issue with the recommended McMaster spring not providing enough tension to pull the flexible filament through the extruder. This could also be solved with purchasing a more rigid spring, but was easily solved modifying the design.
  3. Decreased the depth of the channel to allow for the screw to fully tighten. For some reason the recessed channel in the lever arm for the shoulder bolt was too deep, which meant I couldn't fully tighten the screw down.
  4. Decreased the thickness of the extruder block. The lever arm was too thick and came into contact with the heat sink resulting in added friction, making it difficult for the spring to push the arm up.

The combination of the drive gear providing more force and an almost fully enclosed filament guide allows the printer to successfully extrude flexible material. These modifications have greatly improved both my print quality and success rate using flexible filament with the MakerBot Replicator 2X.

I have attached STL files, but can provide STEP files if someone wants.

Refer to the instructions from rmcniff for post processing and installation if needed. However, I did not have to do any post processing and was able to use my parts as is. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:222667

Note: This is for the right extruder, you can simply mirror the STL files if needing an upgrade for the left extruder.

Happy printing!

The lack of good joystick mounts was frustrating, so I made my own.

This mount is for the HOTAS X55 Joystick and Throttle, and designed to camp on a desk 25mm thick (~1in), but could be edited for a thicker desk. I've included the Fusion 360 file, so this can be done easily.

Since the X55 joystick and throttle have the same base body and size dimensions this can be printed for both joysticks.

Their are two parts to the clamp. The Spine and Clamp Body. Which need to be welded or glued together. (split up mainly so smaller printers can print each part individually, and to also test tolerances).

The clamp body and spine are threaded to accept the bolts in the files.
The Joystick bolts are ~7mm m10X1.5.
The Desk Clamp Bolts are ~10mm m10X1.5.

The tolerances are really tight for the bolts, and will need to be tried and adjusted depending on what printer your using, and how snug you want them in the joystick(s) itself.

I haven't tested this print yet, waiting on my Mk3!

Cheers!

description.text:
Goals

We needed something to hold our 5th generation Apple TV 4K behind the TV. As it happens, our display is mounted on a wall using the VESA 300mm mounts, which left a set of 100mm holes available on our mounting bracket. Of course you could also use this to mount the Apple TV directly to the back of a free-standing display with 100mm mounts.

There are many of these sort of thing out there, but this one has some specific differences that we wanted.

  • VESA 100 holes.
  • Vent holes in the back, as the Apple TV 4K has a fan we don't want to block.
  • Ability to drop the device in with the cables coming out the top or bottom.
  • 35mm thickness suits newer Apple TVs.

If I were to change it...

  • It's not a tight fit, there is about 1mm of play between the device and the walls. Perhaps tighter would be better.
  • I didn't leave quite enough space around the holes for a washer.
    If the bottom corners were rounded to the profile of the device, there would be space for bottom mounting screws, and it would sit better.
  • Add 100mm holes to the bottom so four screws could be used.
  • Turning the vent holes vertically and printing "standing up" would produce less waste from supports.

This is a simple plastic nut for threaded rod or bolts
As is it should fit a M10 rod. There tight to start but once the rod cuts the threds in they smooth out great.
I did 3 versions flange gnarled and finger turn no flange.

i also left the original 3ds max file in it has all steps from tube to complete

Fit and finish

The most i've had to do with any of these is take a needle file to them if they seem a bit tight
Otherwise just resize to fit.

my size is based on a 0.6 nozzle so print one adjust scale as needed then print your tray's worth.

Why did i do this.

Well .. in short i didnt have any M10 nuts and they didnt need to hold any real waight.
So i thought about it tried finding a modle on here that would thred on a real rod and couldnt.
so i started thinking about how to make one.

my first problem was the threads for the most part there to fine for FDM to print. so i desided to let the bolt / rod cut it's own threds. the next problem was hand turning these things is hard.
so i took a note from those plastic bushing barrings i've seen and made fingers on the inner ring.
Then adjested untill the fingers just barly filled half the thred grove they were still hard to start but once on they go on and off smoothly thereafter.

you do have to take it slow or they will thred crooked but even then it's not that big a deal.
The fingers let the bolt/rod slide and cut the plastic alot easer and they hold up remarkibly well.
i made one with flat sides to get a wrinch on it and turnd it to braking and the whole thing broke before it lost thread hold. took quite a bit of force to brake it to boot.
i've only printed in PLA so abs or petg will yeld diffrent results.
These are now going to be holding my second prusa's y axis together.

HOW TO PRINT IT. The 3D models are already oriented. This model will require a little bit of support for the top part of the window and also for the roof corners. I used Ultimaker Cura to slice the model, and I enabled the Fuzzy Skin (Experimental Feature) option to give the model that texture. If you don't use that option you will get a smooth wall.

MATERIAL. In this project, I tested Polymaker PolyLite PLA. I used gray PolyLite PLA on the Raise3D N2 Plus, and combined with Cura's features and the quality of the filament, the result is just awesome. Polymaker PolyLite PLA is a very simple filament that offers what we need the most: reliability and a high-quality experience.
